solutions.content:
Let's start from creating a disjoint set of all islands, using compressed path and ranking improvements. Also, we will store the size of each connected set on its parent, in the same way like we storing the rank.

While building such union, we will keep track of max island we have encountered till now. After finishing first iteration over the table, we will make another iteration on each zero, and summarize sizes of all distinctive islands, touching current cell, add 1 for the current cel and take max between it and curent max island size.

Upon finishing second iteration, we have an answer. 
Time complexity will be O(m \* α(m, size)), where m is number of operations (additions, unions and finds), bound by O(size), and size = n * n, so, the time complexity will be ≈O(n * n), or linear with the grid size.
The meory complexity is bound by O(n * n) as well.

[Disjoint set explained](https://www.cs.princeton.edu/courses/archive/spring13/cos423/lectures/UnionFind.pdf)

```
function largestIsland(grid: number[][]): number {
    const size = grid.length;
    const dSet = new DisjointSet<number>();

    let maxIsland = 0;
    for (let i = 0; i < size; i++) {
        for (let j = 0; j < size; j++) {
            if (grid[i][j] === 1) {
                const key = calcKey(i, j, size);
                dSet.add(key);
                getNeighbors(key, size).filter(dSet.has.bind(dSet)).forEach((neighbor: number) => dSet.union(key, neighbor));
                maxIsland = Math.max(dSet.getSetSize(key), maxIsland);
            }
        }
    }

    for (let i = 0; i < size; i++) {
        for (let j = 0; j < size; j++) {
            if (grid[i][j] === 0) {
                maxIsland = Math.max(maxIsland, 1 + combineNeighbors(dSet, i, j, size));
            }
        }
    }

    return maxIsland;
};

