# Intuition
We are given index pairs whose elements can be swapped.
We shall be sure that for any string with no cap on the number of swaps , if  swaps occur amongst the connected index then after some number of swaps we reach the lexographically smallest string .
$$ Example:
String : bacd , pairs [1,4],[2,4],[3,4]   
$$
as all the indices are connected to one another (part of a connected component) , this string can reach the lexographically smallest string using the swaps.
The transformation of the above string through the swaps will be as follows:
- bacd
- bdca (2,4 swapped)
- adcb (1,4 swapped)
- abcd (2,3 index swapped) .
Hence, we can be sure that for any connected indices we can reach the lexographically smallest string after some swaps.


# Approach

1. Store the indices in the form of graph using the given pairs.
2. Find the connected components using Depth First Search.
3. Store the chracters and their indices in sorted order in respective vectors.
4. Fill the ans string by traversing the indices vector , and place the characters from the character array one by one.

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int n;
    vector<int>a[100005];
    vector<int>res;
    vector<int>index;
    int vis[100001];
    string x;
    void dfs(int v){
            vis[v]=1;
            res.push_back(x[v]);
            index.push_back(v);
            for(auto u:a[v])
                {
                    if(!vis[u])
                    dfs(u);
                }
    }
    string smallestStringWithSwaps(string s, vector<vector<int>>& pairs) {
        n=s.size();
        string ans=s;
        x=s;
        for(auto u:pairs)
        {
           a[u[0]].push_back(u[1]);
           a[u[1]].push_back(u[0]);
        }
        for(int i=0;i<n;i++)
        {
            if(!vis[i]){
            res.clear();
            index.clear();
            dfs(i);
            sort(res.begin(),res.end());
            sort(index.begin(),index.end());
            int runner=0,ct=0;
            while(runner!=index.size())
            {
                ans[index[runner++]]=res[ct++];
            }
            }
        }
        return ans;


    }
};
```

