solutions.content:
# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
The idea behind this solution is to use DFS to identify all the connected components in the graph of indices formed by the pairs given in the input. For each connected component, we add the characters at the corresponding indices to a multiset sorted in decreasing order of characters, and we also add the indices to another multiset sorted in decreasing order of their values. Once we have added all the characters and indices to the multiset, we update the string by assigning the smallest character in the multiset to the index with the smallest value in the other multiset. We repeat this process for all the connected components until all the indices are assigned a character.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
1. Create an adjacency list representation of the graph formed by the given pairs.
2. Initialize a visited array and two multisets, one for characters and one for indices.
3. For each index in the string, if it has not been visited yet, call the DFS function on it.
4. Inside the DFS function, add the character at the current index to the characters multiset and add the index to the indices multiset.
5. For each neighbor of the current index, call the DFS function recursively.
6. After the DFS function has finished processing all the indices in a connected component, update the string by assigning the smallest character in the characters multiset to the index with the smallest value in the indices multiset.
7. Repeat steps 4-6 until all the indices have been assigned a character.
8. Return the updated string.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
The time complexity of the algorithm is O(NlogN) where N is the length of the input string s. This is because for each connected component, we add the characters and indices to two separate multisets, which takes O(NlogN) time. We do this for each connected component, so the total time complexity is O(NlogN).

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
The space complexity of the algorithm is O(N) where N is the length of the input string s. This is because we use an adjacency list to represent the graph, which takes O(N) space, and we also use two multisets of size N, which takes O(N) space. Additionally, we use a visited array of size N, which also takes O(N) space.

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    multiset<int, greater<int>>vk; // for storing index
    multiset<char, greater<char>>ms; // for storing their character
    void dfs(int idx, vector<vector<int>>&adj, vector<int>&vis, string &s){
        if(vis[idx]==1) return;
        vis[idx]=1;
        ms.insert(s[idx]);
        vk.insert(idx);
        for(auto it:adj[idx]){
            dfs(it,adj,vis,s);
        }

    }
    string smallestStringWithSwaps(string s, vector<vector<int>>& pairs) {
        vector<vector<int>>adj(s.size());
