solutions.content:
First consider if we have pairs [1,2],[2,3],[3,4], it means we can swap each pair of indices in set{1,2,3,4}, like we can swap 1,4 even if it is not shown as a pair.

The idea is grouping(union) a bunch of sets of indices that can swap with each other and sorting the characters within each set, and finally put them back together.

```
class Solution {
    public String smallestStringWithSwaps(String s, List<List<Integer>> pairs) {
        int[] p = new int[s.length()];
		// initialize parent map
        for (int i = 0; i < p.length; i++) {
            p[i] = i;
        }
		// Union
        for (List<Integer> pair : pairs) {
            int p1 = find(pair.get(0), p);
            int p2 = find(pair.get(1), p);
            if (p1 != p2) p[p2] = p1;
        }
        Map<Integer, List<Integer>> map = new HashMap<>();
		// Group each set of indices can swap together
        for (int i = 0; i < p.length; i++) {
            int pi = find(i, p);
            map.putIfAbsent(pi, new ArrayList<>());
            map.get(pi).add(i);
        }
        char[] chs = new char[s.length()];
        for (int key : map.keySet()) {
		    // List of indices in that group
            List<Integer> value = map.get(key);
            List<Integer> list = new ArrayList<>(value);
			// sorting the indices based on character in input string
            Collections.sort(list, (o1, o2) -> (s.charAt(o1) - s.charAt(o2)));
            for (int i = 0; i < list.size(); i++) {
			// put value to each index
                chs[value.get(i)] = s.charAt(list.get(i));
            }
        }
		// return new string
        return new String(chs);

    }

    private int find(int i, int[] p) {
        while (i != p[i]) {
            p[i] = p[p[i]];
            i = p[i];
        }
        return i;
    }
}
